                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d520">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.1153 Smith Company, Werner G./19:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-07-01T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 1, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>419. Your 926, June 29, 4 p.m., wood oil of Werner G. Smith Company. If you have
                    not already done so, please repeat to Tokyo your telegram under reference. Also
                    say, as from the Department, that in the light of the information contained in
                    your 926, the Department assumes that the American Embassy will in its
                    representations stress the Department’s concern not only by reason of the delay
                    but by reason of the unwarranted conditions which those responsible for the
                    detention of the wood oil are seeking to attach to its release.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
